<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0808-A"><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>&quot;We will not accept that our people's ethnic and religious background be used as a card in the hands of foreign forces to interfere in Iraq and to prolong the occupation,&quot; Kana said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0581"><line>Pope John Paul II, who named Casmusa archbishop in 1999, late last year condemned attacks on Catholic churches in Mosul, including an attack on the home of the leader of the Chaldean community -- the Catholic breakaway from the Assyrian Church.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>&quot;I am sad in my heart because tomorrow I will not be attending Mass,&quot; said Widad, a Chaldean Christian.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Iraq has Syrian Catholics and Orthodox and Armenian Catholics and Orthodox, and recently, after the British mandate, protestants, and Catholics of the Latin Church.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>The major Christian groups include Chaldean-Assyrians, who make up Kana's group, and Armenians.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="19,32,48,57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>The attacks killed 12 people and injured 61 others.</line><line>Dana George, 60, would like to leave the country _ if only for the sake of her three grown children.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Christians and churches were attacked many times amidst chaos and instability that prevailed in the war-torn country since the US-led war on Iraq in March 2003, while extremists claim that they are fighting against US troops and whoever is cooperating with them, and also accuse the United States of launching a Crusade on Muslims.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="6" label="Iraqi Christians  increasingly targeted " weight="4"/><scu uid="4" label="Several churches have been attacked" weight="3"/><scu uid="15" label="Those targeted have included people helping the U.S.-led forces" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>Even for parties with deeper pockets, like the Assyrian Democratic Movement, television advertising is too costly.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>In Baghdad, he said, &quot;we have the cover of law and Iraqi regular army and security forces.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>Because of its lack of financial clout, the party's Shara (the Truth) radio broadcasts in Kurdistan, but its frequency has trouble making it to Baghdad.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>In Baghdad, a spokesman for one of the main Christian political parties suggested the abuction might be an attempt to intimidate the community into staying at home on polling day.</line><line>Amid the violence, the deputy prime minister acknowledged that polling day was likely to be mired in violence but argued an &quot;imperfect&quot; poll was better than none at all.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>About 200 more have died in the general violence that has gripped Iraq.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0581"><line>Archbishop Basil George Casmusa, 66, leader of the city's Syrian Catholic community, was seized by gunmen at around 5 pm (1400 GMT) as he was about to enter his car, Father Faraj told AFP.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="19,3,48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>Protestants also began to gain a foothold.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>The Assyrian civilization, which has existed since 3,000 B.C., has one of the oldest Christian traditions in the world, dating to the first century.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>Christians in Iraq have a rich, ancient and complex history.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="37"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>She and her sister would like to leave for good for Australia, where their two other sisters live.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>The top US commander in Iraq, General George W. Casey, gave a similarly gloomy prognosis, saying that election day violence was unavoidable despite the coalition's best efforts.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>&quot;Considering the fact that members of the next parliament will only keep their posts for no longer than 11 months, it's not worth spending all that money,&quot; he adds.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>They still speak the ancient biblical language of Aramaic.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>The Pope is our only power, but doesn't help us,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>The former archbishop of Canterbury launched a campaign Monday to assure the future of Iraq's Assyrian community, which he said is facing persecution.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="41,57"><scu uid="14" label=" campaign to assure the future of Iraqi Christian community" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>She said she and her sister, Widad, 60, who lives with her, will not catch the 6:30 a.m. bus that takes them to church every Sunday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>Christians flourished in Iraq long before anyone, anywhere was Muslim.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="0,22,49"><scu uid="9" label="Assyrian Christians in Iraq date to the pre-Islamic first century" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>An area known as the Sunni triangle west and north of Baghdad has been a stronghold for Iraqi insurgents battling U.S. occupation and the interim Iraqi government they consider American puppets.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0581"><line>All of Iraq's Christian denominations -- Assyrian, Syrian, Armenian and Greek -- have wings which recognize the supremacy of the Holy See.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>Archbishop Basile Georges Casmoussa, 66, leader of Mosul's Syrian Catholic community, was seized by gunmen at around 5 pm (1400 GMT) as he was about to enter his car, local priest Father Faraj told AFP.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="19,3,48"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041207.0480"><line>On November 8, at least three people were killed and 45 wounded when two suspected car bombs exploded within minutes of each other outside two churches in southern Baghdad.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Poverty and consecutive wars let many Christians leave Iraq.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>&quot;The foreigner is trying to create division and enmity between Christians and Muslims.</line><line>At night, she said, she wakes up four or five times to look out the window to make sure no one's standing outside.</line><line>&quot;Now I feel it's my duty to pay him back,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>&quot;These are issues of human rights and abuse of people which we have to be aware of.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>&quot;It would be better to die in church than anywhere else,&quot; she said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0581"><line>Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro Valls said the Holy See &quot;condemns in the firmest manner this terrorist act and demands that Monsignor Casmusa be rapidly returned safe and well to his ministry&quot;.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>E-mail: steve--gushee@pbpost.com</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Freedom of religion is stipulated in the interim constitution adopted last March and applied until a permanent one next year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>Thousands of Kurds were killed when Saddam Hussein's forces gassed the town of Halabja in 1988.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>&quot;Christmas is not only a tree and decoration, but it is an occasion through which we emphasize the importance of restoring security in Iraq and staying unified in spite of different religions and ethnic groups,&quot; said one of Christian.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>In an interview, Yonadem Kana, the leader of the Assyrian Democratic Movement in Iraq and a member of the Iraqi National Council, said the fighters have been deployed in Baghdida near the northern city of Mosul.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="13,5"><scu uid="8" label="Christian minority was organized into political parties" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>With much riding on their performance, Iraqi security forces went on the offensive, killing 35 rebels and arresting 64 in the space of 48 hours in the formerly rebel-held city of Fallujah, west of Baghdad, the government said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Although Christians represent only 3 percent of the Iraqi population, some of them are elite of cultured and professional experts who are very much respected by the people.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>The mainly Christian community has faced relentless persecution for hundreds of years from the largely Muslim population living alongside them.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>&quot;Governmental parties are able to reach out to the public through the media because they have greater financial resources,&quot; says Odeesho Toma, a member of the Assyrian Patriotic Party, which is running on a coalition list with Kurdish parties.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>Though Kurdish leaders say they only seek autonomy, many Kurds harbor aspirations for independence.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>But Yonadem Kana, secretary general of the Assyrian Democratic Movement, said the general security situation of the country _ car bombings, kidnappings and murders, which affect all of Iraq's religious groups _ had chased away many Christians.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="35"><scu uid="8" label="Christian minority was organized into political parties" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>Two beheaded corpses of Iraqi soldiers were also found in the city, security sources said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>With the country in turmoil now, Muslims are asking why the Christians aren't taking sides on the question of Fallujah or other trouble spots where anti-American insurgency is strong.</line><line>Saturday's &quot;explosions will no doubt push people to immigrate,&quot; said Father Raphael Qutaimi, acting bishop of the Syrian Catholic Church.</line><line>Never in Iraq, Kana said, had a church been attacked, not since the days of the Mongols, who massacred 800,000 of Baghdad's residents and destroyed the city in the 13th century.</line><line>We mustn't leave it.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>Outside Iraq, members of the country's huge emigre community began registering for this month's election in 14 countries around the globe in what organisers hailed as one of the largest operations of its kind.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>After Saturday's bombings of five churches _ which damaged buildings but caused no casualties _ Christian leaders fear more will leave.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>The constitution of 1970, adopted by former regime, guarantees freedom of religion and prohibits any religious discrimination.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>This is simply to say that the Assyrians are now the victims of terrorists and the imprint of others who want to put their very narrow world view upon others.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Christians in Iraq did not celebrate Christmas this year as they did last year, as they cancelled the midnight mass early Saturday, main feature of the celebrations, due to curfew.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="30,55"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>OTHERS: Ethnic Turks as well as Assyrians belonging to the Chaldean-Assyrian church, the main Christian sect in Iraq, are tiny minorities, with Turkmens concentrated in parts of northern Iraq.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="10,12,14,20,36,42,44"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>Delegates from 18 Iraqi factions and U.N. experts will attend.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041207.0480"><line>Gunmen stormed into the city's Chaldean and Armenian churches in the latest attacks on Iraq's minority Christian community, they said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="14" sums="10,14,22,29,30,32,36,37,40,44,51,55,57,6"><scu uid="4" label="Several churches have been attacked" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>&quot;We have to hold meetings and symposiums for our people in the north to urge them to vote for the list we are part of,&quot; Toma says.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>In any event, Christianity in Iraq, through what is known as the Assyrian Church of the East, took root very shortly after the faith was born.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="10,37,41,6"><scu uid="9" label="Assyrian Christians in Iraq date to the pre-Islamic first century" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>She said she would like to leave Iraq for good.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>&quot;They figure instead of staying and paying $50,000 (euro40,275) to kidnappers for ransom, they can spend $5,000 (euro4,025) in Latakia or Damascus,&quot; he said, referring to two cities in neighboring Syria.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>Many Sunni leaders want the Jan. 30 vote postponed, and militant Sunni clerics have called for a boycott.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Religious minorities in Iraq, especially Christians, account for 3 percent of the population of 25 million, most of them Shiites and Sunnis.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="14,29,30,32,36,44,55"><scu uid="2" label="Christians constitute about three percent of Iraq's population" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>The Rev. Doctor Khoshaba George, who runs an Assyrian church in London, said the community's hopes of a brighter future had been raised with the fall of Saddam.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>St. Thomas the apostle, Sts.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>KURDS: A Kurdish minority that accounts for up to 20 percent of the population is predominantly Sunni Muslim.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>Already the victims of several church bombings since August, the country's 700,000 Christians, who make up just three percent of Iraq's 26 million people, are struggling to get their message across.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>&quot;Anywhere _ out of the Arab world _ where they all think we are infidels,&quot; she said.</line><line>They will wait it out and return when the situation improves.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>The Syrian Catholic Church of which the kidnapped bishop is a member has a significant presence in Iraq.</line><line>Insurgents abducted Syrian Catholic Archbishop Basile Casmoussa apparently to frighten Iraqi Christians.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="12" label="Insurgents want to frighten Iraqi Christians in upcoming elections" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>SUNNI MUSLIMS: Estimated at more than 30 percent of the population, including most Kurds.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>Another three were burnt to death in a vehicle, the officers said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>Numbers are hard to verify, but there are significantly fewer than two million Christians among the 24 million Iraqis today.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>Unlike big governmental partithan one million.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>The language of liturgy there was and, in some cases, remains Aramaic, the tongue Jesus spoke.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>Ethnic Turks, displaced by Saddam from oil-rich provinces in the past, seek to maintain their strength in the northern oil town of Kirkuk.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>Kana, who is on a three-day visit to Syria for talks on Iraq's security, said his movement will not station fighters in other Iraqi cities.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>So for now, she will continue going to her St. Matthew's Church despite the attacks.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>Iraq's 25.4 million people include ethnic Arabs, Kurds and Turks and are religiously split among the Sunni and Shiite branches of Islam.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="19,48,49"><scu uid="20" label="Iraq's population of 25 million" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>Thaddaeus, however, has a murky history.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>The attacks killed 12 people and injured 61 others.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>We must stand hand in hand and heart to heart and not give the outsider cause to divide us,&quot; Qutaimi said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>According to opinion of some of Islamist trends, Islam is attached to Arabism and this had driven Christians out of the Arab nationality, which created an identity crisis to them.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>&quot;In recent months and years churches and monasteries have been attacked and people have been killed,&quot; said Carey, who launched the campaign with Assyrian leaders at the House of Lords.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>Another poster shows Iraq's map in white and the ancient symbol of a sun engulfing a star and two rivers springing near the northern, restive, city of Mosul in tribute to the Tigris and the Euphrates rivers.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>But they cannot afford it.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>Kana said his movement does not need to be protected by U.S.-led coalition forces.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>It is putting pressure upon them to get them to leave.&quot;</line><line>Carey said the Assyrians were also seen as an easy target because they are Christians in a mainly Muslim country.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>The advent of Islam in the seventh century began the decline of Christianity in the Middle East.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>North of Baghdad, some 20 rebels ambushed an army checkpoint near Baquba, sprayed gunfire and lobbed rocket-propelled grenades, killing seven soldiers and a security guard, army officers told AFP.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041207.0480"><line>The Chaldean church, one of the largest in Mosul, was built in the 1950s and enlarged four decades later.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>When Sanctions were imposed on Iraq in 1990 due to Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, many Christians, who were living in perfect harmony with Muslims, left the country to join their relatives in the West.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="10"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>They are shelling our church, they might break into our homes tomorrow and the next day force us to wear the veil,&quot; Widad said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>The Chaldean patriarch in Baghdad, Emmanuel Delly, said Casmoussa &quot;was abducted outside his home as he was returning from a pastoral visit in the diocese of Mosul&quot;.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="16,57"><scu uid="5" label="the Syrian Archbishop of Mosul was kidnapped" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>Christians make up just 3 percent of Iraq's population of about 25 million.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="13,37,43,6"><scu uid="2" label="Christians constitute about three percent of Iraq's population" weight="3"/><scu uid="20" label="Iraq's population of 25 million" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>The home of the Chaldean patriarch was attacked late last year prompting condemnation from Pope John Paul II.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>Sadly, they may not have a future.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041207.0480"><line>&quot;We were then taken outside and the armed men set off the devices.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>On the Net:</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>Gumen kidnapped a Catholic archbishop in Iraq's main northern city of Mosul Monday in what the Vatican condemned as a &quot;terrorist act&quot; as persistent violence dogged the run-up to landmark January 30 elections.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="11,23,41,43"><scu uid="5" label="the Syrian Archbishop of Mosul was kidnapped" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050114.0291"><line>The few posters of Christian parties on display bear no symbols other than the map of Iraq.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="25,32"><scu uid="8" label="Christian minority was organized into political parties" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>For the first time in their lives, Widad Mikho and her sister Neshwan will not attend Mass on Sunday, too frightened after a series of church bombings across Baghdad.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041207.0480"><line>At the same moment, gunmen attacked an Armenian church, forcing out a security guard and two other people inside the building, the guard said, adding: &quot;I heard two explosions.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0581"><line>Armed men kidnapped a Catholic archbishop in Iraq's main northern city of Mosul Monday, a local priest said, prompting denunciations from the Vatican of what it called a &quot;terrorist act&quot;.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="43,49"><scu uid="5" label="the Syrian Archbishop of Mosul was kidnapped" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>&quot;They want us to leave Iraq,&quot; said Surah Samaan, a 25-year-old lab technician, referring to the attackers, who she believes are Arabs linked to al-Qaida.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>It was united with the Roman Catholic Church in 1871.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>On Oct. 16, bomb attacks targeted five churches in Baghdad _ which damaged buildings but caused no casualties.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>St. Thaddaeus generally gets credit for bringing the new faith to Assyrians living throughout Mesopotamia, the vast area that is now part of Iraq, Iran and Syria.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>Bassem Samir Khouri, a legal adviser in the interim Education Ministry, will also skip Sunday mass but is staying put in Iraq.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>The story of Christianity in and around Iraq is a mixture of history and myth but certainly began in the very early days of the faith.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>There are 800,000 Assyrians in Iraq and there are thought to be around half a million living around the world.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>Another church was bombed in Baghdad in September.</line><line>&quot;But this country has been ours for thousands of years.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>He is also known as the Apostle Jude, the brother of James and author of the New Testament letter of Jude.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>In Mosul, the US military said it had killed seven insurgents in the space of 24 hours.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>&quot;There's nobody to help us. Muslims have the support of their tribe.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>&quot;We do not want to transform our movement into a militia,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>She has been living in a state of near paranoia since the August church attacks.</line><line>But her husband won't hear of it.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>The armed attacks led to the exodus of thousands of Christmas to Syria and Jordan.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041207.0480"><line>Armenian Christians in Iraq number only a few thousand.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="32,40"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>More than 1,500 members of an Iraqi Christian group have gone to northern Iraq to try to protect Christians following attacks on churches in Baghdad and Mosul, the leader of the group said Saturday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="12" sums="11,12,19,22,23,25,37,42,48,49,51,6"><scu uid="4" label="Several churches have been attacked" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>George Carey said the Assyrians were the victims of systematic ethnic cleansing, which had worsened considerably since the fall of Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>Some groups remained loyal to the Orthodox tradition, while others, such as the Chaldean Catholic Church, professed loyalty to the Catholic church in the West.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Christians hold only one portfolio in the interim government of Iyad Allawi.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>The cities of Najaf and Karbala are the center of Iraqi Shiite's religious authority.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>&quot;They are denying us what is most important thing in our lives.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050125.0196"><line>Campaign organizer Mark Seddon called for Assyrian rights to be enshrined in the new Iraqi constitution and for Assyrians dispossessed by the violence to be given the financial aid to return to their lands and homes.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>A soldier was knelt in morning prayer in a tiny sentry post when insurgents came up from behind and decapitated him.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>Samaan said Christians are vulnerable in predominantly Muslim Iraq.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="22"><scu uid="6" label="Iraqi Christians  increasingly targeted " weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>Neshwan Mikho, 46, has been cleaning the Saint John's Church in the working class neighborhood of Bataween every Saturday for the past seven years undeterred by rain, sandstorms or even shellings.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>Both bishops are members of a branch of the Roman Catholic Church and one of several small, eclectic church groups in the country.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>He and all the dozen Christians interviewed Saturday said the attacks were not the work of Muslim Iraqis, but foreigners.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050123.0023"><line>Here is a look at its ethnic and religious makeup.</line><line>CHRISTIANS: About 3 percent of the population, most belong to the Chaldean-Assyrian church.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041204.0231"><line>Islamic militants have told Christian owners of liquor stores to close down their businesses, and they have threatened Christians who run beauty salons and shops selling fashionable clothes.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="33"><scu uid="16" label="People seen as breaking Islamic law are being attacked" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>The killings came after the Iraqi army arrested around 60 people in sweeps in the town of Bohrouz, south of Baquba, where the insurgency has popular support, said local resident Akeel Mateb.</line><line>We don't know who took him, nor the reason why,&quot; Delly told the missionary news agency Misna by telephone.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20041225.0121"><line>Most of Christians in Iraq are in Baghdad and northern cities.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,22,43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>But fear will not keep Dana George away.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="16"/></line><line>&quot;What can we do?</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20041207.0480"><line>In a coordinated assault on August 1, six car bombs killed 10 people and injured 50 others outside churches in Baghdad and Mosul.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro Valls said the Holy See &quot;condemns in the firmest manner this terrorist act and demands that Monsignor Casmoussa be rapidly returned safe and well to his ministry&quot;.</line><line>In another attack, seven policemen were killed and 15 wounded in a suicide bombing outside a police station in Baiji, home to Iraq's largest oil refinery, a senior police officer said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050127.0071"><line>They wanted to discourage Christians from voting on Sunday, according to Iraqi bishop, Louis Sako of Kirkuk.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050117.0603"><line>&quot;I hope elections will go smoothly but we are prepared for the worst,&quot; Saleh told AFP.</line><line>&quot;It could be an attack on Christians who are willing to participate in the elections,&quot; said Assyrian Democratic Movement spokesman William Warda.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="3"><scu uid="12" label="Insurgents want to frighten Iraqi Christians in upcoming elections" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20041016.0191"><line>Iraq's Christians,